{"title_page": "Eskbank railway station", "text_new": "{{about|the station in Scotland|the preserved station in New South Wales|Eskbank railway station, New South Wales}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n|name      = Eskbank\n|other_name = {{lang-gd|Bruach Easg}}<ref name=Brailsford />\n|image_name = Eskbank station.jpg\n|symbol    = rail\n|locale    = Eskbank, [[Dalkeith]]\n|borough   = [[Midlothian]]\n|lowusage1516 = {{pad}}0.128 million<ref group=\"note\">The statistics only reflect six months of operation</ref>\n|usage1617 = {{increase}} 0.275\n|usage1718 = {{increase}} 0.339\n|usage1819 = {{increase}} 0.367\n|manager   = [[Abellio ScotRail]]\n|platforms = 1\n| years       = July 1849\n| events      = Opened as '''Gallowshall'''\n| years2      = October 1850\n| events2     = Renamed '''Eskbank & Dalkeith'''<ref>Disused Stations: Site Record, [http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/e/eskbank_and_dalkeith/index.shtml Eskbank and Dalkeith], updated 18 May 1997, accessed 22 October 2018</ref>\n| years3      = 6 January 1969\n| events3     = Closed\n| years4       = 6 September 2015\n| events4      = Reopened as '''Eskbank''' on New Site\n|code      = EKB\n|gridref   = NT323660\n|coordinates = {{coord|55.883|-3.083|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Eskbank railway station''' ({{lang-gd|Bruach Easg}},<ref name=Brailsford>{{cite book |editor-last=Brailsford |editor-first=Martyn |title=Railway Track Diagrams 1: Scotland & Isle of Man |edition=6th |date=December 2017 |origyear=1987 |publisher=Trackmaps |location=Frome |isbn=978-0-9549866-9-8 |chapter=Gaelic/English Station Index |ref=harv }}</ref> code EKB) is a station serving the Eskbank area of the town of [[Dalkeith]], [[Midlothian]], Scotland. It reopened on the [[Borders Railway]] between [[Edinburgh]] and [[Tweedbank]], just beyond [[Galashiels]]. There is a half-hourly service to [[Tweedbank railway station|Tweedbank]]. It is approximately a mile from Dalkeith town centre. Car parking space is available for 248 cars and also cycle storage space.<ref>ScotRail, [https://www.scotrail.co.uk/plan-your-journey/stations-and-facilities/ekb Eskbank], accessed 22 October 2018</ref>\n\nThe station sits approximately 12.5&nbsp;[[km]] from [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Waverley]] and 43.5&nbsp;km from Tweedbank,<ref>{{cite web|title=Eskbank|accessdate=2 August 2012|publisher=Transport Scotland|url=http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/projects/borders-railway/the-project/route-and-stations/eskbank|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322213109/http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/projects/borders-railway/the-project/route-and-stations/eskbank|archive-date=22 March 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and lies close to the towns of [[Bonnyrigg]] and [[Dalkeith]].\n\nThe original Eskbank and Dalkeith railway station was previously closed (along with the Waverley Route) in 1969. The new construction work was undertaken by [[BAM Nuttall]]. The new station, further south than the original, opened on 6 September 2015.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-34108746| website=BBC News| date=6 September 2015| title=Borders to Edinburgh railway opens as longest line in UK in a century}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150214123854/http://www.bordersrailway.co.uk/faqs.aspx Borders Railway]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100322213109/http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/projects/borders-railway/the-project/route-and-stations/eskbank Eskbank Station] (Transport Scotland)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A3JzxPMUJRg Video footage of Eskbank railway station]\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line|next={{rws|Newtongrange}}|previous={{rws|Shawfair}}|route=[[Abellio ScotRail]]<br /><small>[[Borders Railway]]</small> |col={{ScotRail colour}} |lightcol={{National Rail colour|ScotRail|branch=Edinburgh Crossrail}} }}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line\n|next={{stnlnk|Dalhousie}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small>\n|previous={{stnlnk|Glenesk}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small>\n|route=[[North British Railway]]<br /><small>[[Waverley Route]]</small>\n|col={{NBR colour}} |lightcol={{NBR light}} }}\n{{Disused Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line one to two\n|next1={{stnlnk|Smeaton}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small>\n|next2={{stnlnk|Crossgatehall Halt}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small>\n|route=[[North British Railway]]<br /><small>[[Macmerry Branch]]</small>\n|col={{NBR colour}} |lightcol={{NBR light}} }}\n{{rail line\n|previous={{stnlnk|Bonnyrigg}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small>\n|route=[[North British Railway]]<br /><small>[[Peebles Railway]]</small>\n|col={{NBR colour}} |lightcol={{NBR light}} }}\n{{rail line\n|previous={{stnlnk|Broomieknowe}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small>\n|route=[[North British Railway]]<br /><small>[[Esk Valley Railway (Scotland)|Esk Valley Railway]]</small>\n|col={{NBR colour}} |lightcol={{NBR light}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:Borders Railway]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Midlothian]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened by Network Rail]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1849]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1969]]\n[[Category:Beeching closures in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2015]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Abellio ScotRail]]\n[[Category:Reopened railway stations in Great Britain]]\n[[Category:1969 disestablishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Dalkeith]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United Kingdom opened in the 2010s]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|the station in Scotland|the preserved station in New South Wales|Eskbank railway station, New South Wales}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n|name      = Eskbank\n|other_name = {{lang-gd|Bruach Easg}}<ref name=Brailsford />\n|image_name = Eskbank station.jpg\n|symbol    = rail\n|locale    = Eskbank, [[Dalkeith]]\n|borough   = [[Midlothian]]\n|lowusage1516 = {{pad}}0.128 million<ref group=\"note\">The statistics only reflect six months of operation</ref>\n|usage1617 = {{increase}} 0.275\n|usage1718 = {{increase}} 0.339\n|usage1819 = {{increase}} 0.367\n|manager   = [[Abellio ScotRail]]\n|platforms = 1\n| years       = July 1849\n| events      = Opened as '''Gallowshall'''\n| years2      = October 1850\n| events2     = Renamed '''Eskbank & Dalkeith'''<ref>Disused Stations: Site Record, [http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/e/eskbank_and_dalkeith/index.shtml Eskbank and Dalkeith], updated 18 May 1997, accessed 22 October 2018</ref>\n| years3      = 6 January 1969\n| events3     = Closed\n| years4       = 6 September 2015\n| events4      = Reopened as '''Eskbank''' on New Site\n|code      = EKB\n|gridref   = NT323660\n|coordinates = {{coord|55.883|-3.083|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Eskbank railway station''' ({{lang-gd|Bruach Easg}},<ref name=Brailsford>{{cite book |editor-last=Brailsford |editor-first=Martyn |title=Railway Track Diagrams 1: Scotland & Isle of Man |edition=6th |date=December 2017 |origyear=1987 |publisher=Trackmaps |location=Frome |isbn=978-0-9549866-9-8 |chapter=Gaelic/English Station Index |ref=harv }}</ref> code EKB) is a station serving the Eskbank area of the town of [[Dalkeith]], [[Midlothian]], Scotland. It reopened on the [[Borders Railway]] between [[Edinburgh]] and [[Tweedbank]], just beyond [[Galashiels]]. There is a half-hourly service to [[Tweedbank railway station|Tweedbank]]. It is approximately a mile from Dalkeith town centre. Car parking space is available for 248 cars and also cycle storage space.<ref>ScotRail, [https://www.scotrail.co.uk/plan-your-journey/stations-and-facilities/ekb Eskbank], accessed 22 October 2018</ref>\n\nThe station sits approximately 12.5&nbsp;[[km]] from [[Edinburgh Waverley railway station|Waverley]] and 43.5&nbsp;km from Tweedbank,<ref>{{cite web|title=Eskbank|accessdate=2 August 2012|publisher=Transport Scotland|url=http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/projects/borders-railway/the-project/route-and-stations/eskbank|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322213109/http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/projects/borders-railway/the-project/route-and-stations/eskbank|archive-date=22 March 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and lies close to the towns of [[Bonnyrigg]] and [[Dalkeith]].\n\nThe original Eskbank and Dalkeith railway station was previously closed (along with the Waverley Route) in 1969. The new construction work was undertaken by [[BAM Nuttall]]. The new station, further south than the original, reopened on 6 September 2015.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-34108746| website=BBC News| date=6 September 2015| title=Borders to Edinburgh railway opens as longest line in UK in a century}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150214123854/http://www.bordersrailway.co.uk/faqs.aspx Borders Railway]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100322213109/http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/projects/borders-railway/the-project/route-and-stations/eskbank Eskbank Station] (Transport Scotland)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A3JzxPMUJRg Video footage of Eskbank railway station]\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line|next={{rws|Newtongrange}}|previous={{rws|Shawfair}}|route=[[Abellio ScotRail]]<br /><small>[[Borders Railway]]</small> |col={{ScotRail colour}} |lightcol={{National Rail colour|ScotRail|branch=Edinburgh Crossrail}} }}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line\n|next={{stnlnk|Dalhousie}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small>\n|previous={{stnlnk|Glenesk}}<br