{"title_page": "Toledano", "text_new": "{{Expand French|Toledano (homonymie)|date=January 2011}}\n{{Expand Hebrew|\u05d8\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05e0\u05d5|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox surname\n|name = Toledano\n|image = Tolede.Santa Maria la Blanca.int\u00e9rieur2.JPG\n|image_size = <!-- width in pixels --> \n|caption = \n|pronunciation = \n|meaning = \"Toledan\" \"from [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] (or from [[Kingdom of Toledo|''Reino de'' Toledo]])\"\n|region = Spain, Morocco, Greece, Israel, France; Spanish-speaking countries\n|languageorigin = Spanish, Ladino\n|variant = [[Toledani]]; [[Toledo (surname)|Toledo]], [[de Toledo]]\n|footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Toledo - Omer Toledano.jpg|thumb|The city of Toledo, Spain where the Toledano family name originated.]]\n\n'''Toledano''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d8\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05e0\u05d5}}, {{lang-lad|\u05d8\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05d3\u05d0\u05e0\u05d5}}) is a family name derived from the city of [[Toledo, Spain]]. Bearers of the name can be found mainly in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking countries, the [[United States]], [[France]], [[Canada]], [[Israel]], and [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emanuelschool.nsw.edu.au/Ma+Nishmas/20070824/Vol+15_Issue+26.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=20 July 2008|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=7 October 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720090515/http://www.emanuelschool.nsw.edu.au/Ma%20Nishmas/20070824/Vol%2015_Issue%2026.pdf|archivedate=20 July 2008}}</ref> Among [[Mizrahi Jews]], and in particular [[Sephardi]] Jews in their various diasporas, the Toledano surname is still prevalent, indicating an ancestry traced back to Toledo, Spain. The Toledano name was also retained among non-Jews in various Spanish-speaking countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zazzle.com/toledano_the_ancient_synagogue_card-137105842251887188|title=Toledano & the Ancient Synagogue Card|website=Zazzle.com|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Jewish Toledanos were expelled from Spain in 1492. After the expulsion from Spain the Toledanos went to [[Safed]], [[Salonika]], and [[Morocco]]. They arrived in [[Fes|Fez, Morocco]] during the 16th century from Salonika and from there went to [[Meknes]] and became leaders of the community from the 16th century until the present day.\n\n==Notable bearers==\n* Rabbi [[Raphael Baruch Toledano]], Chief Rabbi of Morocco\n* [[Avi Toledano|Avraham \"Avi\" Toledano]] (born 1948, [[Meknes]]), Moroccan-Israeli singer, Eurovision nominee\n* [[Avraham Toledano]], the Mashgiach ruchani of the Yeshivat Haraayon Hayehudi\n* [[Drew Tal]] (born Dror Toledano, 1957), a prominent photographer and visual artist working and living in New York City\n* [[\u00c9ric Toledano]] (born 1971), a French film director, actor<ref>[[:fr:\u00c9ric Toledano]]</ref>\n* [[Fernando Usero|Fernando Usero Toledano]] (born 1984, Brazatortas, Ciudad Real, Castile-La Mancha), a Spanish professional footballer\n* [[Haham Pinchas Toledano]], chief rabbi of Amsterdam\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Antolin Toledano]] (born 1936, Quintana del Puente, Palencia, Spain), a Spanish industrialist\n* [[Maria Pia de Saxe-Coburgo e Bragan\u00e7a|Hilda Toledano]] (a literary pseudonym; 1907\u20131995)\n* [[Ralph de Toledano]] (1916, Tangiers - 2007, Bethesda, Maryland), Jewish Moroccan-American political activist\n* [[Ralph Toledano]] (born September 27, 1951, Casablanca, Morocco) French-Moroccan businessman\n* [[Samuel Toledano]] (1929, [[Tangiers]] - 1996, Madrid), Jewish Moroccan-Spanish community leader\n* [[Shmuel Toledano]] (born 1921, Tiberias), an Israeli Mossad employee and politician\n* {{ill|Sidney Toledano|fr}} (born 1951), CEO of the [[Christian Dior S.A.]]<ref>[[:fr:Sidney Toledano]]</ref>\n* [[Vicente Lombardo Toledano]] (1894\u20131968), Mexican politician and teacher\n* [[Ya'akov Moshe Toledano]] (born 1880, Tiberias - 1960), an Israeli Sephardic-haredi rabbi, chief rabbi of Cairo, Alexandria and Tel Aviv\n* [[Yuriorkis Gamboa|Yuriorkis Gamboa Toledano]] (born 1981), Cuban boxer\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tullis-Toledano Manor]] (also known as ''the Toledano-Philbrick-Tullis House''), a red clay brick mansion\n* [[Toledana]]\n* [[Toledo (disambiguation)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=253&letter=T Toledano] ([[Jewish Encyclopedia]])\n\n{{surname|Toledano}}\n\n[[Category:Spanish-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Jewish surnames]]\n[[Category:Sephardic surnames]]\n[[Category:Surnames of Spanish origin]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand French|Toledano (homonymie)|date=January 2011}}\n{{Expand Hebrew|\u05d8\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05e0\u05d5|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox surname\n|name = Toledano\n|image = Tolede.Santa Maria la Blanca.int\u00e9rieur2.JPG\n|image_size = <!-- width in pixels --> \n|caption = \n|pronunciation = \n|meaning = \"Toledan\" \"from [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] (or from [[Kingdom of Toledo|''Reino de'' Toledo]])\"\n|region = Spain, Morocco, Greece, Israel, France; Spanish-speaking countries\n|languageorigin = Spanish, Ladino\n|variant = [[Toledani]]; [[Toledo (surname)|Toledo]], [[de Toledo]]\n|footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Toledo - Omer Toledano.jpg|thumb|The city of Toledo, Spain where the Toledano family name originated.]]\n\n'''Toledano''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d8\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05e0\u05d5}}, {{lang-lad|\u05d8\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05d3\u05d0\u05e0\u05d5}}) is a family name derived from the city of [[Toledo, Spain]]. Bearers of the name can be found mainly in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking countries, the [[United States]], [[France]], [[Canada]], [[Israel]], and [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emanuelschool.nsw.edu.au/Ma+Nishmas/20070824/Vol+15_Issue+26.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=20 July 2008|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=7 October 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720090515/http://www.emanuelschool.nsw.edu.au/Ma%20Nishmas/20070824/Vol%2015_Issue%2026.pdf|archivedate=20 July 2008}}</ref> Among [[Mizrahi Jews]], and in particular [[Sephardi]] Jews in their various diasporas, the Toledano surname is still prevalent, indicating an ancestry traced back to Toledo, Spain. The Toledano name was also retained among non-Jews in various Spanish-speaking countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zazzle.com/toledano_the_ancient_synagogue_card-137105842251887188|title=Toledano & the Ancient Synagogue Card|website=Zazzle.com|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Jewish Toledanos were expelled from Spain in 1492. After the expulsion from Spain the Toledanos went to [[Safed]], [[Salonika]], and [[Morocco]]. They arrived in [[Fes|Fez, Morocco]] during the 16th century from Salonika and from there went to [[Meknes]] and became leaders of the community from the 16th century until the present day.\n\n==Notable bearers==\n* Rabbi [[Raphael Baruch Toledano]], Chief Rabbi of Morocco\n* [[Avi Toledano|Avraham \"Avi\" Toledano]] (born 1948, [[Meknes]]), Moroccan-Israeli singer, Eurovision nominee\n* [[Avraham Toledano]], the Mashgiach ruchani of the Yeshivat Haraayon Hayehudi\n* [[Drew Tal]] (born Dror Toledano, 1957), a prominent photographer and visual artist working and living in New York City\n* [[\u00c9ric Toledano]] (born 1971), a French film director, actor<ref>[[:fr:\u00c9ric Toledano]]</ref>\n* [[Fernando Usero|Fernando Usero Toledano]] (born 1984, Brazatortas, Ciudad Real, Castile-La Mancha), a Spanish professional footballer\n* [[Haham Pinchas Toledano]], chief rabbi of Amsterdam\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Antolin Toledano]] (born 1936, Quintana del Puente, Palencia, Spain), a Spanish industrialist\n* [[Maria Pia de Saxe-Coburgo e Bragan\u00e7a|Hilda Toledano]] (a literary pseudonym; 1907\u20131995)\n* [[Ralph de Toledano]] (1916, Tangiers - 2007, Bethesda, Maryland), Jewish Moroccan-American political activist\n* [[Ralph Toledano]] (born September 27, 1951, Casablanca, Morocco) French-Moroccan businessman\n* [[Samuel Toledano]] (1929, [[Tangiers]] - 1996, Madrid), Jewish Moroccan-Spanish community leader\n* [[Shmuel Toledano]] (born 1921, Tiberias), an Israeli Mossad employee and politician\n* {{ill|Sidney Toledano|fr}} (born 1951), CEO of the [[Christian Dior S.A.]]<ref>[[:fr:Sidney Toledano]]</ref>\n* [[Vicente Lombardo Toledano]] (1894\u20131968), Mexican politician and teacher\n* [[Ya'akov Moshe Toledano]] (born 1880, Tiberias - 1960), an Israeli Sephardic-haredi rabbi, chief rabbi of Cairo, Alexandria and Tel Aviv\n* [[Yuriorkis Gamboa|Yuriorkis Gamboa (Toledano)]] (born 1981), Cuban boxer\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tullis-Toledano Manor]] (also known as ''the Toledano-Philbrick-Tullis House''), a red clay brick mansion\n* [[Toledana]]\n* [[Toledo (disambiguation)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=253&letter=T Toledano] ([[Jewish Encyclopedia]])\n\n{{surname|Toledano}}\n\n[[Category:Spanish-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Jewish surnames]]\n[[Category:Sephardic surnames]]\n[[Category:Surnames of Spanish origin]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable bearers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toledano"}
{"title_page": "2020 Ryder Cup", "text_new": "{{use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox team golf tournament\n| name = Ryder Cup\n| year = 2020\n| logo = Official_Logo_of_the_2020_Ryder_Cup.png\n| logowidth   = 300px\n| dates = September 25\u201327, 2020\n| venue = [[Whistling Straits]]\n| location = [[Haven, Wisconsin]]\n| home = USA\n| away = Europe\n| homecaptain = [[Steve Stricker]]\n| awaycaptain = [[P\u00e1draig Harrington]]\n| homescore = \n| awayscore = \n| result = \n}}\n{{Location map\n|USA\n|relief     = 1\n|label      = <small>Whistling Straits</small>\n|lat        = 43.851\n|long       = -87.735\n|caption    = Location in the [[United States]]\n|float      = \n|marksize   = 5\n|background = \n|width      = 240\n}}\n{{Location map\n|USA Wisconsin\n|relief     = 1\n|label      = <small>Whistling Straits</small>\n|lat        = 43.851\n|long       = -87.735\n|caption    = Location in [[Wisconsin]]\n|position   = left\n|float      = \n|marksize   = 5\n|background = \n|width      = 160\n}}\nThe '''43rd [[Ryder Cup]] Matches''' will be held in the [[United States]] from September 25 to 27, 2020, on the Straits course at [[Whistling Straits]], [[Haven, Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rydercup.com/news-media/usa/everything-you-need-know-about-2020-ryder-cup |title=Everything you need to know about the 2020 Ryder Cup |publisher=Ryder Cup}}</ref> Team Europe is the reigning cup holder after its 17\u00bd\u201310\u00bd victory over Team USA in [[2018 Ryder Cup|2018 at Le Golf National]].\n\n==Format==\nThe [[Ryder Cup]] is a [[match play]] event, with each match worth one point. The competition format will be as follows:\n*'''Day 1''' (Friday) \u2013 4 [[Foursome (golf)|foursome]] (alternate shot) matches and 4 [[four-ball golf|fourball]] (better ball) matches\n*'''Day 2''' (Saturday) \u2013 4 foursome matches and 4 fourball matches\n*'''Day 3''' (Sunday) \u2013 12 singles matches\n\nOn the first two days there are 4 foursome matches and 4 fourball matches with the home captain choosing which are played in the morning and which in the afternoon.\n\nWith a total of 28 points available, 14\u00bd points are required to win the Cup, and 14 points are required for the defending champion to retain the Cup.  All matches are played to a maximum of 18 holes.\n\n==Course==\n{{main|Whistling Straits}}\n\n==Team qualification and selection==\n*'''Note:''' Due to the impact of the [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports#Golf|coronavirus pandemic]] on both the PGA and European tours, qualifying criteria is subject to change.\n===United States===\nThe United States qualification rules were announced on February 20, 2019. The qualification rules are similar to those used for the 2018 Ryder Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rydercup.com/news-media/usa/how-players-will-qualify-2020-us-ryder-cup-team |title=How players will qualify for the 2020 U.S. Ryder Cup team |publisher=PGA of America |date=February 20, 2019}}</ref> The majority of the team are selected from the Ryder Cup points list which is based on prize money won in important tournaments. Generally one point is awarded for every $1,000 earned. The team consists of:\n\n* '''The leading eight players on the Ryder Cup points list, gained in the following events'''\n**2019 [[Men's major golf championships|major championships]]\n**2019 [[World Golf Championship]] events and [[The Players Championship]] (half points)\n**2020 [[Men's major golf championships|major championships]] (double points for the winner, 50% extra for those who make the cut; it is unknown if the formula will be adjusted due to the cancellation of the [[2020 Open Championship]])\n**2020 [[PGA Tour]] events. Qualifying events in this category are those played between January 1 and August 23, 2020, the date of the [[BMW Championship (PGA Tour)|BMW Championship]], and including the Zurich Classic of New Orleans team event and WGC events. \"Alternate\" events (those played opposite a major or WGC event) do not earn points\n* '''Four captain's picks'''\n**To be announced after the 2020 [[Tour Championship]], which concludes on September 1.\n\n===Europe===\nThe European team qualification rules were announced on May 8, 2019. The number of captain's picks was reduced from four to three. The team will consist of:<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/48202346 |title=Ryder Cup 2020: Padraig Harrington to cut wildcard picks from four to three |date=May 8, 2019 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rydercup.com/news-media/europe/europe-ryder-cup-2020-qualification-process-confirmed |title=Europe Ryder Cup 2020 qualification process confirmed |publisher=European Tour |date=May 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* '''The leading four players on the Race to Dubai Points List'''\n**Points earned in all [[Race to Dubai]] tournaments starting in September 2019 with the [[BMW PGA Championship]] and ending with the BMW PGA Championship in September 2020. Points earned in the later events of 2020 will be multiplied by 1.5.\n* '''The leading five players, not qualified above, on the World Points List'''\n**Total World Points earned in [[Official World Golf Ranking]] events starting in September 2019 with the [[BMW PGA Championship]] and ending with the BMW PGA Championship in September 2020. Points earned in the later events of 2020 will be multiplied by 1.5. No World points will be earned from tournaments staged opposite Rolex Series tournaments in both [[2019 European Tour|2019]] and 2020.\n* '''Three captain's picks'''\n**To be announced in the week after the final qualifying event.\n\n==Teams==\n[[File:HarringtonStrickerRyderCup2020.png|thumb|right|350x350px|Team captains at the one year to go 2020 Ryder Cup press conference]]\n===Captains===\n[[Steve Stricker]] was named as the US captain on February 20, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/47305535 |title=Ryder Cup: Steve Stricker named US captain for 2020 against Europe |date=February 20, 2019 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref>. Stricker selected [[Jim Furyk]] as his first vice-captain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rydercup.com/news-media/usa/2020-us-ryder-cup-captain-revealed |title=Steve Stricker selected as the 2020 US Ryder Cup Captain |publisher=Ryder Cup |access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\n[[P\u00e1draig Harrington]] was named as the European captain on January 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/46788433 |title=Padraig Harrington: Europe name Irishman as 2020 Ryder Cup captain |date=January 8, 2019 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> In September 2019, Harrington selected [[Robert Karlsson]] as his first vice-captain.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/golf/49746030 |title=Ryder Cup 2020: Robert Karlsson named as one of Europe's vice-captains |date=September 18, 2019 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref>\n<!--\n===Vice-captains===\n\n===Players===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=8|{{flagicon|USA|size=50px}} United States team\n|-\n!Name\n!Age\n!data-sort-type=\"number\"|Points<br/>rank\n!data-sort-type=\"number\"|World<br/>ranking\n!data-sort-type=\"number\"|Previous<br/>Ryder Cups\n!data-sort-type=\"number\"|Matches\n!data-sort-type=\"number\"|W\u2013L\u2013H\n!data-sort-type=\"number\"|Winning<br/>percentage\n|-\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  || colspan=\"6\" | Non-playing captain\n|-\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|-\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|- style=\"background:#ffa;\"\n| align=left|{{sortname||}}\n|  ||  ||  ||  ||  ||  || \n|- style=\"ba