{"title_page": "1989 Asia Golf Circuit", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\nThe '''1989 Asia Golf Circuit''' was the 28th season of [[golf]] tournaments that comprised the [[Asia Golf Circuit]].\n\nAmerican [[Brian Claar]] claimed the overall circuit championship.\n\n==Tournament schedule==\nThe table below shows the 1989 Asia Golf Circuit schedule.<ref>{{cite book |title=World of Professional Golf 1990 |first=Mark H. |last=McCormack |authorlink=Mark McCormack |publisher=Sackville |date=1990 |page=276\u2013284, 516\u2013527 |isbn=0948615389}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44378544/1989-asia-golf-circuit/ |title=1989 Asia Golf Circuit |newspaper=Tampa Bay Times |location=St.Petersburg,Florida |date=31 March 1989 |page=29 |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> For the first time, the circuit had eleven tournaments with the addition of the [[Pakistan Open]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Date!!Tournament!!Country!!Prize<br/>fund ([[US$]])!!Winner!!Notes!!Refs\n|-\n|9\u201312 Feb || [[Philippine Open (golf)|San Miguel/Coca-Cola Philippine Open]] || Philippines || align=right|140,000  || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Emlyn Aubrey]] ||  ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890213-1.1.31 |title=First win |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=13 February 1989 |page=31 |via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890214-1.1.31 |title=Scores |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=14 February 1989 |page=31 |via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|16\u201319 Feb|| [[Hong Kong Open (golf)|Johnnie Walker Hong Kong Open]] || Hong Kong || align=right|175,000 || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Claar]] ||  || <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890220-1.1.29|title=Claar's gift for his lucky wife|newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=20 February 1989 |page=29 |via=National Library Board  |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|23\u201326 Feb || [[Thailand Open (golf)|Thai International Thailand Open]] || Thailand || align=right|150,000 || {{flagicon|USA|}} [[Brian Claar]] ||  || <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890227-1.1.30 |title=Claar adds Thai Open to his double |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=28 March 1989 |accessdate=9 April 2020|page=30 |via=National Library Board}}</ref>\n|-\n|2\u20135 Mar || [[Pakistan Open]] || Pakistan || align=right|120,000 || {{flagicon|PHI}} [[Frankie Minoza]] || New tournament; held the same week as the [[Rolex Masters]]. ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890317-1.1.27 |title=World at a glance  |newspaper=New Straits Times |location=Malaysia |date=7 March 1989 |page=19 |via=Google  Archive|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|9\u201312 Mar ||[[Indian Open (golf)|Wills Indian Open]] || India || align=right|120,000 || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[R\u00e9my Bouchard]] ||  ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/biztimes19890313-1.1.27 |title=Bouchard clinches Indian Open title |newspaper=The Business Times |location=Singapore |date=13 March 1989 |page=27|via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|16\u201319 Mar || [[Singapore Open (golf)|Singapore Open]] || Singapore || align=right|220,000 || {{flagicon|TWN}} [[Lu Chien-soon]] ||  ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890320-1.1.34 |title=Chien-soon gets his second win |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=20 March 1989 |page=34 |via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|22\u201325 Mar || [[Indonesia Open (golf)|Indonesian O